00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:36.670
And we conduct basic, clinical, genomic, and population-based

45
00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:40.320
research. And today, I'm going to talk a little bit more about that, and then also

46
00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:43.960
end with how you can join us if you're interested in training at NCI.

47
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.870
So, we get this question a lot, and a lot of people wonder where we are

48
00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:53.400
actually located when they're looking for summer internships or fellowships.

49
00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:57.109
And we are located in Maryland. So there are actually three campuses

50
00:02:57.140 --> 00:03:01.070
across Maryland within 20 to 25 minutes away from each other, and

51
00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:04.900
that's the NIH Bethesda Campus, which you see the NIH Clinical

52
00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:08.750
Center in the middle. You have the NCI Shady Grove Campus, and then about

53
00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:12.480
20 minutes up the road and up 270 is the NCI

54
00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:15.980
Frederick Campus. And across those three campuses, we have over

55
00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:19.900
200 principal investigators and over 800 fellows in all of

56
00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:21.500
those different research groups.

57
00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:27.410
So, what do we do? So we conduct cancer research with

58
00:03:27.420 --> 00:03:30.490
a purpose, similar to the extramural funding.

59
00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:32.630
We actually conduct

60
00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:35.540
research across the cancer continuum as well.

61
00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:39.660
So we pursue high-risk, high-reward research that is unlikely to be

62
00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:43.600
traditionally funded. So that's going to be things that don't have

63
00:03:43.660 --> 00:03:47.590
clear clinical applications up front or things that

64
00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:51.049
take a longer time. We can tackle those kinds of difficult

65
00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:54.940
problems. We also support research that benefits small numbers

66
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.570
or underserved patients. So think your rare cancers or

67
00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:03.660
certain minority groups. And then we also address emergent

68
00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:05.900
public health issues or threats.

69
00:04:06.760 --> 00:04:10.560
So that allows us to be able to really conduct the full

70
00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:14.100
scope of cancer care. And our research areas

71
00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:16.280
run along those very similar lines.

72
00:04:16.840 --> 00:04:20.019
So everything from basic translational clinical work through

73
00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:23.740
bioinformatics, biostatistics, cancer prevention, cancer

74
00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:26.380
control, global health, and population science.

75
00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:32.100
So all of those research areas are actually housed across a

76
00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:35.660
number of divisions, offices, and centers, and those are the ones that are spread

77
00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:39.580
out across those three campuses. So the Intramural Research

78
00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:43.480
Program traditionally consists of the Center for Cancer Research, or CCR,

79
00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:47.240
and the Division of Cancer Epidemiology and Genetics, or DCEG.

80
00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:51.320
So you will find almost 90% of our fellows within those two

81
00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:54.500
divisions, with majority of them in the Center for Cancer Research.

82
00:04:55.100 --> 00:04:58.830
However, there are limited opportunities to train within the Division of

83
00:04:58.900 --> 00:05:02.510
Cancer Control and Population Science, as well as the Center for Global

84
00:05:02.600 --> 00:05:02.920
Health.

85
00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:07.260
Our last two divisions here, the Center to Reduce Cancer Health Disparities, as

86
00:05:07.300 --> 00:05:11.060
well as the Division of Cancer Prevention, host specific

87
00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:15.080
training fellowship programs, which allow their fellows to then train in

88
00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:16.900
those other four divisions as well.

89
00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:20.640
So there are a lot of opportunities in those different research areas.

90
00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:25.500
And across all of those divisions, we strive to attract,

91
00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:29.900
train, and retain the best minds to become the next generation of cancer

92
00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:31.820
researchers. So at the

93
00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:36.420
NCI, you will find undergraduates, post-bacs, graduate students,

94
00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:37.240
medical students,

95
00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:39.480
postdocs, as well as

96
00:05:40.660 --> 00:05:43.720
research fellows and clinical research fellows within our training programs.

97
00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:49.900
And our research environment is one that is really second to none in

98
00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:52.480
terms of the quality of scientific training and mentoring.

99
00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:56.620
We are a highly collaborative institution with lots of

100
00:05:56.640 --> 00:06:00.580
opportunities to work with multidisciplinary teams and partner with scientists

101
00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.700
across the world. So this is one of those

102
00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:07.250
questions that we got a lot during the career fair yesterday, was like, "Okay, is

103
00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:09.760
it similar to academia?" And I

104
00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:14.800
came to NCI as a graduate student, so I have limited experience of what it's like

105
00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:18.780
in academia. But from what I recall, it was pretty similar, except you

106
00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:22.300
get to add on those added benefits of those extra resources and those

107
00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:26.544
levels of collaboration.In addition to that, we

108
00:06:26.604 --> 00:06:30.284
also have world-class technology with access to over 40 cores,

109
00:06:30.744 --> 00:06:32.904
and we really are committed to preparing

110
00:06:34.584 --> 00:06:38.484
our fellows for their next education or career goal.

111
00:06:40.644 --> 00:06:44.404
So here in the Center for Cancer Training, we oversee a lot of

112
00:06:44.484 --> 00:06:48.204
the different career and professional development opportunities, as well

113
00:06:48.444 --> 00:06:50.624
as recruitment opportunities.

114
00:06:51.604 --> 00:06:55.554
And one of the, I think, really unique structures to the training environment is

115
00:06:55.604 --> 00:06:59.204
that there is so much support for our fellows here on campus.

116
00:06:59.214 --> 00:07:02.484
So starting within those individual divisions, offices, and centers, there are

117
00:07:02.544 --> 00:07:05.724
training staff, training directors. I'll show a picture of some of them later.

118
00:07:05.804 --> 00:07:06.944
Two of them are in our audience.

119
00:07:07.944 --> 00:07:11.324
And there is a lot of support at that level.

120
00:07:11.364 --> 00:07:14.924
But our office, together with the NIH Office of Training and Education

121
00:07:15.544 --> 00:07:19.144
or OITE, which you may be familiar with, we host a number

122
00:07:19.504 --> 00:07:22.764
of career workshops and trainings that are offered across

123
00:07:22.804 --> 00:07:26.504
those core competencies, such as career exploration,

124
00:07:26.624 --> 00:07:30.564
communication, leadership and management, mentoring and teaching, as

125
00:07:30.624 --> 00:07:31.544
well as wellness.

126
00:07:34.084 --> 00:07:37.904
So I did want to add a little bit, touch on the logistics of being an

127
00:07:37.964 --> 00:07:41.834
NCI intern or a fellow, because these are some common questions that we often get

128
00:07:41.944 --> 00:07:45.904
asked. All of our positions are paid internships or fellowships.

129
00:07:46.324 --> 00:07:50.144
We are unable to provide housing with any of those, but we do point you in the

130
00:07:50.224 --> 00:07:54.084
direction of helpful resources to help you identify if you have to relocate

131
00:07:54.124 --> 00:07:54.714
to Maryland.

132
00:07:55.734 --> 00:07:59.054
Our public transportation, like the Metro, the bus, is

133
00:07:59.084 --> 00:08:03.064
subsidized or parking is provided if that is something that you are interested

134
00:08:03.124 --> 00:08:06.834
in. And I think one of the crucial things that we remind all of our

135
00:08:06.884 --> 00:08:10.404
applicants is that you must be able to pass a federal background check in order to

136
00:08:10.444 --> 00:08:12.644
participate in the IRP.

137
00:08:14.024 --> 00:08:17.964
I can't talk too much about eligibility because it will vary by education

138
00:08:18.044 --> 00:08:21.874
stage or program. So I highly encourage you to look up the program or

139
00:08:21.944 --> 00:08:23.464
division that you're interested in working in.

140
00:08:23.854 --> 00:08:27.764
But just know that there is some variation between the citizen requirements or

141
00:08:27.824 --> 00:08:30.304
enrollment or time since most recent degree.

142
00:08:30.324 --> 00:08:32.544
So you just really want to make sure you're paying attention to that.

143
00:08:37.084 --> 00:08:40.985
And one of the things that I wanted to mention is that we have recently

144
00:08:41.004 --> 00:08:44.264
developed the Train at NCI application portal.

145
00:08:44.904 --> 00:08:48.704
And it's a website that is designed to really help you navigate how to figure

146
00:08:48.804 --> 00:08:52.394
out what type of internship or fellowship you might be interested

147
00:08:52.464 --> 00:08:55.884
in. So you can scan a QR code or visit

148
00:08:55.894 --> 00:08:59.684
trainatnci.cancer.gov to view a lot of our training

149
00:08:59.724 --> 00:09:03.264
opportunities and just learn more about the kind of research that we do.

150
00:09:03.284 --> 00:09:07.084
And if you're interested in joining us, there are four core ways that you

151
00:09:07.124 --> 00:09:09.004
can join the Intramural Research Program.

152
00:09:09.484 --> 00:09:11.764
The first is to contact investigators directly.

153
00:09:12.604 --> 00:09:14.554
That gets a little complicated now.

154
00:09:15.424 --> 00:09:18.484
You can apply to central NCI or NIH databases.

155
00:09:18.564 --> 00:09:21.964
You submit your CV or application materials, and then you would contact

156
00:09:22.004 --> 00:09:25.164
investigators to encourage them to look at your materials.

157
00:09:25.804 --> 00:09:28.124
You can also explore open fellowship positions.

158
00:09:28.324 --> 00:09:32.244
I think this is the best way to be able to navigate trying

159
00:09:32.284 --> 00:09:36.084
to find a post-bac or post-doc, or you can apply to a cohort

160
00:09:36.144 --> 00:09:40.064
training program. And I wanted to leave you with talking a little bit about the

161
00:09:40.124 --> 00:09:41.324
cohort training programs.

162
00:09:43.064 --> 00:09:44.364
So the first is the summer

163
00:09:45.184 --> 00:09:47.964
program, so the Cancer Research Interns program.

164
00:09:48.024 --> 00:09:49.804
So this is an up to 12-week

165
00:09:50.644 --> 00:09:52.984
full-time research opportunity.

166
00:09:53.044 --> 00:09:56.624
And with the CRI program, it gives you the opportunity to receive

167
00:09:56.684 --> 00:09:59.404
additional mentorship as well as professional development support.

168
00:09:59.904 --> 00:10:02.804
It is open to undergrads, graduate students, and medical students.

169
00:10:03.194 --> 00:10:06.353
And you don't need to have previous research experience.

170
00:10:06.684 --> 00:10:09.404
However, it is helpful, but it is not a requirement.

171
00:10:09.434 --> 00:10:12.274
The applications for the summer typically open in mid-November

172
00:10:13.164 --> 00:10:16.964
with the applications closing for CRI in January, as with the

173
00:10:17.004 --> 00:10:19.824
general summer internship program typically closes in February.

174
00:10:22.244 --> 00:10:26.204
The next program I wanted to talk about was the Intramural Continuing Umbrella

175
00:10:26.324 --> 00:10:28.324
Research Experiences, or ICURE program.

176
00:10:29.244 --> 00:10:30.174
And that is

177
00:10:31.384 --> 00:10:34.024
currently for post-bac and post-doc research experiences.

178
00:10:34.864 --> 00:10:38.464
You have the opportunity to spend up to two to three years conducting research

179
00:10:38.624 --> 00:10:42.183
on-site at NCI. The start date is

180
00:10:43.043 --> 00:10:45.384
the September following the application cycle.

181
00:10:45.464 --> 00:10:49.104
So, for example, the application just closed for this year's

182
00:10:49.144 --> 00:10:52.664
cohort, but it won't start until September of next year.

183
00:10:54.324 --> 00:10:57.664
It provides multi-level mentorship and career development

184
00:10:58.004 --> 00:11:01.024
support, as well as connection to the extensive CURE network as well.

185
00:11:01.584 --> 00:11:04.924
So the applications for the next cycle will open this fall.

186
00:11:07.804 --> 00:11:11.384
And lastly, we have the Cancer Prevention Fellowship Program or CPFP.

187
00:11:11.904 --> 00:11:15.664
So that is a post-doc research experience that is mentored and multidisciplinary

188
00:11:16.324 --> 00:11:19.564
and really focused on providing specialized training in

189
00:11:19.644 --> 00:11:21.444
epidemiology and biostatistics.

190
00:11:22.264 --> 00:11:26.164
And it gives up to four years conducting full-time research on-site with

191
00:11:26.204 --> 00:11:28.744
additional coaching and career development support as well.

192
00:11:28.864 --> 00:11:32.744
So those applications typically open in May and close in

193
00:11:32.804 --> 00:11:36.734
September. So the sites currently are not updated yet, but they should be within

194
00:11:36.764 --> 00:11:40.144
the next couple of weeks. So you can be on the lookout for that one.

195
00:11:41.524 --> 00:11:43.444
I think no matter what,

196
00:11:45.184 --> 00:11:48.854
one of the best resources that we have at NCI really is our

197
00:11:48.924 --> 00:11:52.604
training directors. And if you know what research area you're

198
00:11:52.644 --> 00:11:56.624
interested in, I just highly encourage you to contact them and

199
00:11:56.844 --> 00:12:00.334
learn more about their respective divisions or any opportunities that they may

200
00:12:00.464 --> 00:12:04.164
have. They're very wonderful people and always willing to

201
00:12:04.184 --> 00:12:04.484
help.

202
00:12:06.384 --> 00:12:08.924
And if you have any questions, you can also contact me as well.

203
00:12:09.704 --> 00:12:13.374
You can visit us at the Train at NCI to learn more about our research and our

204
00:12:13.444 --> 00:12:16.904
programs or join our Listserv to stay up to date on upcoming training

205
00:12:16.944 --> 00:12:19.384
opportunities. And with that, thank you very

206
00:12:19.424 --> 00:12:21.004
much.

